What's Well Covered
Data retrieval        → QueryNode (full SQL expressibility)
Row transformation    → TransformNode (map, filter, rename, cast, dedup)
AI enrichment         → LLMNode (per-row or per-batch)
External calls        → HttpNode (defined, not fully implemented)
Control flow          → ConditionalNode, LoopNode, MergeNode, ParallelNode
Pipeline composition  → SubPipelineNode (defined, not implemented)
What's Missing or Incomplete
1. Data Sources Beyond Postgres
Right now the only way to get data into a pipeline is via QueryNode hitting Postgres. Real workflows pull from many sources:
FileNode             → read CSV, JSON, Parquet, Excel from disk or S3
StreamNode           → consume from Kafka, Redis pub/sub, WebSocket
EmailNode            → read from Gmail/Outlook inbox (you're connected to Gmail)
CalendarNode         → read events from Google Calendar (you're connected)
WebScrapeNode        → fetch and parse a webpage
DatabaseNode         → generic SQL for MySQL, SQLite, other Postgres instances
2. Data Sinks — Writing Output Somewhere
Everything outputs to the CLI right now. Real pipelines write results:
WriteFileNode        → write CSV, JSON, Parquet to disk or S3
WebhookNode          → POST results to a URL
EmailSendNode        → send results as email (you have Gmail MCP)
DatabaseWriteNode    → INSERT/UPDATE/UPSERT back to Postgres
SlackNode            → post to a Slack channel
NotificationNode     → generic push notification
3. Data Quality and Validation
No node type handles data quality today:
ValidateNode         → assert schema constraints, throw on violations
DeduplicateNode      → cross-batch dedup (TransformNode.dedup is in-memory only)
FillNullNode         → fill missing values with defaults or computed values
SampleNode           → random sample N rows or X% of dataset
AssertNode           → pipeline-level assertions, fail if condition not met
ProfilingNode        → compute statistics (min, max, mean, nulls, cardinality)
4. Data Reshaping
TransformNode handles row-level operations but not structural reshaping:
PivotNode            → rows to columns (status → pending_count, completed_count)
UnpivotNode          → columns to rows (wide → long format)
FlattenNode          → unnest arrays or JSON fields into rows
AggregateNode        → group-by outside of SQL (post-fetch aggregation)
WindowNode           → rolling averages, rank, lag/lead over sorted rows
5. Control Flow Gaps
SwitchNode           → multi-way conditional (like switch/case, not just if/else)
                       "route by segment: enterprise→A, smb→B, startup→C"
TryCatchNode         → catch errors from a sub-pipeline, run recovery branch
RetryNode            → retry a failing sub-pipeline N times with backoff
WaitNode             → sleep for duration or until a condition is true
ThrottleNode         → rate limit execution (max N rows/sec to downstream)
BatchNode            → collect N rows then emit as single batch
6. ML and Vector Operations
Given your PTM research background these are natural extensions:
EmbedNode            → embed text fields into vectors (via Voyage/OpenAI)
VectorSearchNode     → similarity search against ChromaDB/pgvector
ClassifyNode         → run a classification model on rows
ScoreNode            → apply a scoring function (sigmoid, softmax, custom)
ClusterNode          → k-means or similar clustering on row vectors
7. Time and Scheduling
No temporal awareness in the engine today:
ScheduleNode         → run pipeline on cron schedule
WindowTimeNode       → filter/group by time windows (last 7 days, this month)
WatermarkNode        → track pipeline last-run watermark for incremental loads
8. Human-in-the-Loop
The confirmation step exists in CLI but not as a first-class node:
ApprovalNode         → pause execution, wait for human confirmation
                       "before sending 500 emails, show preview and wait"
ReviewNode           → surface N samples for human inspection mid-pipeline
FeedbackNode         → collect human rating/correction, feed back to LLM
9. Observability and Side Effects
LogNode              → emit structured log events mid-pipeline
MetricsNode          → record a metric value (Prometheus, StatsD)
AuditNode            → write immutable audit trail per row
CacheNode            → cache output by input hash, skip if cache hit
CheckpointNode       → save intermediate results to resume from on failure


1. HttpNode — call external APIs inside pipelines
   → enrich customer data from Clearbit, send Slack alerts, post to webhooks
   → straightforward to build given the existing node pattern

2. Pipeline persistence (SQLite)
   → save named pipelines, rerun without replanning
   → "save this as 'weekly revenue report'" → reruns with npm run cli weekly

3. Session context / memory
   → "show me the same report but for last month"
   → pronoun resolution across turns in the cli

4. SubPipelineNode
   → compose pipelines from other pipelines
   → build a library of reusable pipeline components

5. Streaming output
   → yield rows as they arrive rather than collecting everything
   → essential for large datasets and long-running LLM enrichments

6. Physical operator improvements
   → push ORDER BY into Postgres scan (huge latency win for large tables)
   → hash join spill to disk for large joins
   
7. REST API layer
   → POST /pipeline/plan, POST /pipeline/execute
   → exposes the engine over HTTP
   → lets other tools (dashboards, Slack bots) drive it

